  {
    "id": "doi:10.3366/edinburgh/9781474487177.003.0002",
    "doi": "10.3366/edinburgh/9781474487177.003.0002",
    "title": "Gothic Overhearing: Inquisition, Confession, and Accusation in Browning’s Dramatic Monologues",
    "abstract": "This chapter identifies the overhearing of the “prisoner next-door” as a Gothic trope essential to Robert Browning’s early dramatic monologues. His early poems often feature dramatic speakers who are mad monks and murderous dukes confessing criminal acts. By entitling his first pair of dramatic monologues “Madhouse Cells,” Browning calls attention to a Gothic genealogy – one inherited from 1790s novels, where the characters of overheard prisoners were ubiquitous. In their novels, Radcliffe and Lewis frequently staged scenes of romantic and criminal confession that served as a testing ground for lyric expression, literalizing and experimenting with the model of triangulation across prison walls. Those semi-satirized figures pour forth their feelings through song and are overhead across castle thresholds, monastic cloisters, and jails of the inquisition, serving as precursors to some of Victorian poetry’s most memorable speakers.",
    "year": "2022",
    "authors": "Olivia Loksing Moy",
    "journal": "The Gothic Forms of Victorian Poetry",
    "source_db": "crossref",
